  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is Wazuh really free?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Wazuh is fully open source under the GPLv2 license, with no per-agent fees or paid tiers. You can monitor unlimited servers and endpoints without licensing costs; you only pay for the infrastructure you run it on or for optional professional support.
  </p>

  <h3>What is the difference between a SIEM and an XDR in Wazuh?</h3>
  <p>
    The SIEM side collects, stores and correlates logs to detect and investigate threats, while the XDR side adds extended detection and automated response across endpoints. Wazuh combines both in a single platform, so it not only finds threats but can also react to them automatically.
  </p>

  <h3>Which compliance standards does Wazuh help with?</h3>
  <p>
    Wazuh's Security Configuration Assessment (SCA) module audits your systems against CIS Benchmarks, PCI-DSS, HIPAA, GDPR and Spain's ENS framework. It produces reports with specific remediation steps, which is useful for passing audits.
  </p>

  <h3>How fast does Wazuh detect a new vulnerability?</h3>
  <p>
    Wazuh keeps a live inventory of installed software and cross-references it against CVE databases in near real time. When a critical exploit like Log4j is published at 10:00, Wazuh can flag the affected vulnerable servers within about 15 minutes.
  </p>

  <h3>Can Wazuh respond to incidents automatically?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Through active response rules Wazuh can block an IP on the firewall, isolate a machine, disable a user or run custom scripts. A common rule is to block an IP for 30 minutes after 5 failed logins in 2 minutes.
  </p>

